==Recording==

The audio recordings were [[Postproduction|reworked]] for the release as a music album, but these were not one-hundred percent perfect: According to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', the records were not completely polished, but had the roar and the fuzziness of rock music, which were not signalized through a [[mix engineer|mixer]], but through [[loudspeaker]].<ref name="rollingstone" /> Two tracks were removed from the album version: ''The Late Great Johnny Ace'', on which Paul Simon was interrupted by a fan, and the repeat of "Late in the Evening" as an encore. The album was internationally commercially successful.{{sfn|Ebel|2004|p=145}} The album peaked at number six of the [[Billboard 200]] chart and sold over 2 million times and was awarded a 2&times;Multi-Platinum. The album was certified Diamond in France, selling more than 1,270,000 there. It was also successful in seven other countries.

=== Film editing ===

The concert was cinematically produced for the future release in television and in the home video market. [[Film director|Direction]] was headed by [[Michael Lindsay-Hogg]], a specialist for music documenations, who worked on the [[The Beatles|Beatles]] film ''[[Let It Be (film)|Let It Be]]''. As a [[Film producer|producer]] he worked with [[James Signorelli]]. The US$750,000 costs for the staging and the video recording were financed by Paul Simon.{{sfn|Ebel|2004|p=139}} It is unknown how much HBO payed for the television and video rights of the recording; according to some sources, these are US$1 million,{{sfn|Eliot|2004|p=174}}{{sfn|Eliot|2004|p=175}} while other state a number of more than US$3 million.<ref name="pileggi-32">{{cite book | author= Nicholas Pileggi | title= Indecent Expenses | publisher= ''[[New York Magazine]]'' | date= February 13, 1984 | page= 32 |url= http://books.google.com/books?id=oOYCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&dq=Indecent+Expenses&hl=de&sa=X&ei=xAGQT43FBcPDtAbchtzdBA&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Indecent%20Expenses&f=false | accessdate=January 5, 2012 }}</ref> The two tracks removed from the live album were included on this film, so that its duration is 87&nbsp;minutes, 12&nbsp;minutes more than the album's.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/44773/Simon-and-Garfunkel-The-Concert-in-Central-Park/overview NY Times | title= Simon and Garfunkel: The Concert in Central Park (1982) | publisher= ''[[New York Times]]'' | accessdate=December 16, 2011 }}</ref> 

The film was for first televised several days after the release of the live album on February 21, 1982, under the title ''Simon and Garfunkel: The Concert in Central Park'' in HBO. The recording was later released in the format [[Video Home System|VHS]] and [[DVD]]. The DVD video does not contain any extras.<ref name="swr3">{{cite web | author= Thomas M<U+00FC>ller | url= http://www.swr3.de/musik/cds-und-dvds/Simon-Garfunkel-The-Concert-In-Central-Park/-/id=47412/did=205358/t6a715/index.html | title= Musik-Check: Simon & Garfunkel: "The Concert In Central Park" | work= [[SWR3]] | date= January 22, 2011 | accessdate=December 16, 2011 |language=German}}</ref> The concert film sold in the US more than 50,000 times and was later awarded a Gold plaque,<ref name="riaa" /> and in Australia it was certified 9&times;Platinum.<ref>{{cite web | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association | url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesDVDaccreds2011.htm | title= ARIA Charts <U+2013> Accreditations <U+2013> 2011 DVDs | date=November 30, 2011 | accessdate=December 16, 2011 }}</ref>

== Critical reception ==

The concert and several recordings were positively met by music critics. In two receptions <U+2013> one on the day after the concert, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' concerning the concert,<ref name="nyt-2">{{cite book | author= Stephen Holden | title= A 60's Sound Is Replayed To Perfection | publisher= ''[[New York Times]]'' | date= September 20, 1981 }}</ref> the other half a year later in the ''Rolling Stone'' cocerning the live album<ref name="rollingstone" /> <U+2013> Stephen Holden praised their performance. According to him, Simon and Garfunkel were successful in tieing their 1970 sound. The duo would continue to complement each other perfectly, despite their different style <U+2013> the romantic-sweetish pop musician Garfunkel and the gloomy, [[Rock 'n' Roll]]-leaning Simon. Several songs by Simon were clearly improved through the arrangements for the concert. The hand-picked backing band were "one of finest groups of musicians ever to play together at a New York rock concer."<ref>{{cite book | author= Stephen Holden | title= A 60's Sound Is Replayed To Perfection | publisher= ''[[New York Times]]'' | date= September 20 , 1981 }}</ref> In a few places, prominently in solo songs such as "Still Crazy After All These Years", Simon's voice felt a little thin, even after mixing, but that was "actually refreshing".<ref>{{cite book | author= Stephen Holden | title= Album Reviews: Simon & Garfunkel <U+2013> The Concert In Central Park | publisher= ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' | issue= 365 | date= March 18, 1982}}</ref> Simon & Garfunkel ran great risks to perform so many acoustic ballads under a cool air in an open-air concert. But just the smooth songs "were beautifully articulated, in near-perfect harmony."<ref>{{cite book | author= Stephen Holden | title= A 60's Sound Is Replayed To Perfection | publisher= ''[[New York Times]]'' | date= September 20, 1981}}</ref> ''New York Times'' overall concluded, "It was a wonderful concert."

These receptions can be generic for many other critics, who rated the concert as favourable. A contemporary reception in the ''Rolling Stone'' on October 1981 called it "one of the finest performances of [1981]." While Simon was an excellent vocalist, Garfunkel sang more restrained on very high passages as earlier, although he found fascinating [[harmony]]. "[T]he [<U+2026><!--twenty-two-song-->] show vividly recaptured another time, an era when well-crafted, melodic pop bore meanings that stretched beyond the musical sphere and into the realms of culture and politics."<ref>{{cite book | title= Simon and Garfunkel | publisher= ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' | issue= 355 | date= October 29, 1981}}</ref> Similarly was the reception of the music magazine ''[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]'' in March 1982, stating "This 19 song, two record set gloriously recaptures the past with sterling renditions of most of the duo's classics as well as a few of Simon's solo compositions filled out by Garfunkel's harmony. For those who grew up listening to Simon & Garfunkel this LP represents a trip down memory lane."<ref>{{cite book | title= Simon & Garfunkel <U+2013> The Concert in Central Park | publisher= [[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] | date= March 6, 1982 | page= 73 }}</ref> 

Several critics criticized parts of the concerts. The contemporary reception of ''Rolling-Stone'' did not like the crossover from "Kodachrome" to "Maybelline", because none of the singers could raise the expressiveness for the rock songs. But this was "[t]he only gaffe of the evening."<ref>{{cite book | title= Simon and Garfunkel | publisher= ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' | issue= 355 | date= October 29, 1981 }}</ref>

== Aftermath ==
=== No union tours, no union album ===
{{See also|Simon %26 Garfunkel#Reunions|title1=Simon & Garfunkel after 1981}}

Immediately after the concert, Simon and Garfunkel were both initially disappointed; the latter explained it in an 1984 interview. Garfunkel was dissatisfied with his singing and he himself did not realized at the beginning the size of the concert : "I didn't get what had happened <U+2013> how big it was <U+2013> until I went home, turned on the television and saw it on all the news [<U+2026>] and later that night on the front pages of all the newspapers. Then I got it."<ref name="playboy" /> [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] released in November 1981 the compilation album ''[[The Simon and Garfunkel Collection]]''. It included the studio takes of 17 Simon & Garfunkel songs, including all songs of the duo until "April Come She Will", which were played during the concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/the-simon-and-garfunkel-collection-17-of-their-all-time-greatest-recordings-r49394|publisher=Rovi Corporation|work=Allmusic|accessdate=April 19, 2012|title=The Simon and Garfunkel Collection: 17 of Their All-Time Greatest Recordings <U+2013> Simon & Garfunkel}}</ref>

After the concert, Simon & Garfunkel went in May 1982 on a world tournee with stations in Japan, Germany, Denmark, Sweden, Switzerland, Netherlands, Ireland, France, Great Britain, New Zealand, the USA and Kanada.{{sfn|Eliot|2004|p=178}} Their first arrival in Europe was in [[Offenbach am Main]] on May 28, 1982 in the [[Stadion am Bieberer Berg]] in front of around 40,000 spectators, their first concert in Germany.{{sfn|Ebel|2004|p=145 et seq}}

[[File:Simon and Garfunkel.jpg|thumb|right|Simon & Garfunkel in a joint concert in 2009]]
During the tournee breaks, Simon & Garfunkel went to a studio to record a duo album, which should include track which were not finished due to the Central Park concert. Throughout the concert travels they presented the first completed songs, but they did not continued to work on the album because of increasing personal tensions between Garfunkel and Simon. Disputes between them often occurred, and sometimes they were not even ready to make interviews.{{sfn|Ebel|2004|p=145 et seq}} After the end of the tournee, Simon & Garfunkel did not resumed their teamwork as a duo. Over a long period of time they both performed for single concerts at best. When Simon again performed in a free concert at the same place as he did ten years before in the Central Park, he refused Garfunkel's offer to participate as a member of the duo.<ref name="nyt-3" /> They went on tour as a duo again in 2003.<ref>{{cite book | author= Ray Waddel | title= Friends Again. Simon and Garfunkel Reunite For Tour | publisher= [[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]| date= September 20, 2003 | pages= 6, 79 }}</ref>

=== Preservation of the Central Park ===
Simon & Garfunkel's ''Concert in Central Park'' brought around US$51,000 to the Central Park.<ref name="pileggi-32" /> Beside Simon & Garfunkel other musicians contributed with benefical concerts and raised the attention for its financial distress. These could mostly eliminated with the help of private financier.<ref>{{cite book | author= Elizabeth Barlow | title= Central Park's Renaissance | publisher= ''[[New York Magazine]]'' | date= June 6, 1983 | pages= 32&nbsp;et seq | url= http://books.google.com/books?id=s8EBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32&dq=Central+Park%E2%80%99s+Renaissance&hl=de&sa=X&ei=sgKQT_3OIMXMsgaE7_SuBA&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Central%20Park%E2%80%99s%20Renaissance&f=false | accessdate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref> In the course of the 1980s, the park was comprehensively repaired and is today considered as a sight.<ref name="gras-240" /><ref name="cph-80er" /> Donations make up the majority of its budget.<ref name="newyork.ch">{{cite web | url= http://www.newyork.ch/central-park/ | title= Central Park | accessdate=December 12, 2011 }}</ref> Today there are still regular concerts and other benefical events.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.centralparknyc.org/about/ | title= About the Central Park Conservancy | publisher= [[Central Park Conservancy]] | accessdate=December 14, 2011 }}</ref>

